                  </div>

                  <div class="questions">
                    <p>
                      To ensure your dryer remains in good working condition, it's crucial to adopt preventive measures, much like how you would care for your refrigerator to avoid future issues. Here are some tips to help prevent dryer problems:
                    </p>

                    <b>Regular Maintenance</b>
                    <ul>
                      <li>Clean the Lint Trap: Just as you would regularly clean the coils and interior of your refrigerator, make it a habit to clean the lint trap after every load. This will improve airflow and reduce the risk of fire.</li>
                      <li>Inspect and Clean the Vent System: Similar to how you'd ensure your refrigerator's air vents are unobstructed, regularly check and clean your dryer's vent system. A clogged vent can cause the dryer to overheat and be less efficient.</li>
                    </ul>

                    <b>Proper Use</b>
                    <ul>
                      <li>Avoid Overloading: Just as overstuffing your refrigerator can hinder its cooling efficiency, overloading your dryer can strain its motor and other components. Stick to recommended load sizes.</li>
                      <li>Use Appropriate Settings: Utilize the correct settings for different types of fabrics, akin to how you’d set the right temperature in your refrigerator for various foods. This helps in preventing unnecessary wear and tear on the machine.</li>
                    </ul>

                    <b>Environmental Considerations</b>
                    <ul>
                      <li>Keep It in a Suitable Location: Ensure your dryer, like your refrigerator, is placed in a well-ventilated area to prevent overheating and maintain efficiency.</li>
                    </ul>

                    <b>Maintain a Stable Power Supply</b>
                    <ul>
                      <li>Just as a refrigerator requires a consistent power supply to function optimally, make sure your dryer is connected to a reliable power source. Avoid using extension cords and check for any electrical issues regularly.</li>
